There was a decrease at DNR signal after interaction. Additionally, a gradual decrease at the oxidation signal of guanine was recorded while interaction time was increased (Fig. 8
                        ). The changes at both signals of DNR and guanine were calculated and presented in Table 2
                        .

EIS technique was also implemented in order to investigate the surface confined interaction of DNR with ctDNA at cQD-PGE by applying different interaction times (Fig. 9
                        ). In the presence of only ctDNA onto the cQD-PGE, the average Rct value was measured as 1242.86 ± 211.71 Ohm (RSD %, 17%, n = 8) which is 4.2 fold higher than the one recorded in the absence of ctDNA by cQD-PGE. This increase at Rct could be a result of the negative charge sites increasing at DNA modified electrode surface related to the phosphate backbone of DNA. After interaction between 10 μM DNR with 40 μg/mL ctDNA during 3, 5, 10 and 15 min, the Rct value was recorded. Accordingly, a gradual decrease was obtained while interaction time was increased. The average Rct values measured before and after interaction with the decrease % ratios were given in Table 3
                        .
